{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":232613,"duration_api_ms":190769,"num_turns":32,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"5fa2d6b4-c79f-4309-825b-9944949c96d7","total_cost_usd":1.08726525,"usage":{"input_tokens":23,"cache_creation_input_tokens":58329,"cache_read_input_tokens":1025338,"output_tokens":8397,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":58329,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":23,"outputTokens":8397,"cacheReadInputTokens":1025338,"cacheCreationInputTokens":58329,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":1.08726525,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed all changes across 7 files (process_backend.rs, service.rs, engine.rs, retry_policy.rs, domain.rs, error.rs, and tests). The implementation is solid: retry limits are correctly increased, exponential backoff with cancellation-awareness is properly implemented, hard timeout enforcement on backend processes works correctly with SIGKILL cleanup and artifact preservation, and BinaryNotFound is correctly classified as terminal at the spawn() site. All 678 tests pass, including comprehensive new tests for timeout, BinaryNotFound, and backoff. Two issues found worth addressing.","amendments":[{"body":"In `map_invoke_error` (service.rs:374-381), the promotion from `InvocationFailed{Timeout, details}` to `InvocationTimeout{backend, contract_id, timeout_ms}` silently discards the `details` string. This loses diagnostic context like \"claude exceeded timeout of 600s\" that was captured at the adapter level. Downstream log entries and error messages will only show the generic \"backend invocation timed out\" format. Consider either (a) preserving details in a new field on `InvocationTimeout`, or (b) logging the original details before promoting, so operators can still diagnose which binary timed out and see the adapter-level context.","rationale":"Information loss in error promotion path. During incident investigation, the adapter-level details (binary name, exact timeout duration format) would help operators diagnose whether a specific backend is consistently timing out. The current implementation makes all timeout errors look identical regardless of which backend or binary was involved, beyond just the backend family name."},{"body":"The `classify_exit_failure` function (process_backend.rs:1449-1451) is a no-op that always returns `TransportFailure` regardless of the `ExitStatus` argument (the parameter is even named `_status`). While the comment explains the design rationale (exit codes after spawn are application-defined), this adds indirection with no behavior change. Either inline `FailureClass::TransportFailure` directly at the two call sites and remove the function, or implement the planned signal-based classification (e.g. SIGSEGV/SIGABRT) that the project prompt envisioned.","rationale":"Dead code / unnecessary abstraction. The function exists at two call sites but provides no classification logic. If kept as a placeholder for future work, it should at least have a TODO comment or track the intent. As-is, it looks like an incomplete implementation that a future reader might try to 'fix' by adding exit code 127 handling, which the comment specifically warns against."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"4249aac2-7af5-4742-8e97-0698151c91eb"}
